    <prj:ScienceGoal mode="Other">
        <prj:name>Dust and gas in GW Ori</prj:name>
        <prj:note>A single science goal is enough to meet all our science requirements: we aim at resolving the large 20-50 AU gap, obtaining details beyond the orbit of GW Ori C (&gt;8 AU) and exploring asymmetries. We use the 12CO(2-1) line and associated continuum, to match our low-resolution SMA data. This will enable us to:
- Detect the fine structure and potential asymmetries of the dust in the inner disk (&lt;100 AU).
- Detect the presence of gas and compare the dust to gas behaviour in the presence of a triple system.
- In unresolved parts of the disk, detect deviations of the gas from Keplerian rotation to track the presence of gravitational perturbations.
Note: The disk is very large and we will *not* recover the outer disk details, but we are only interested in the innermost part of the disk where the disturbances introduced by the companions will be larger (besides outer disk details have been resolved with SMA).</prj:note>
