        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The correlator setup for the 12CO line is selected to a high velocity resolution in order to 
distinguish deviations of Keplerian rotation caused by the gravitational perturbations of the
triple system. For the estimated line widths, we use our previous SMA observations (Fang et al.
2015) and our resulting models, assuming an axisymmetric (unperturbed disk). The dynamical models
predict deviations from Keplerian rotation of the order of 1-10% of the Keplerian velocity (~1%
due to turbulence, ~10% due to pressure/gravitation effects). For the relevant locations (beyond
GW Ori C and at the edge/beyond the SED-estimated gap), we expect Keplerian velocities around
8-13 km/s. We therefore request a setup with a resolution of 79m/s, suitable to detect a ~1%
deviation.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_CORRELATOR</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>Our objective is to detect the innermost disk structure of the circum-triple disk around GW Ori
A,B,C, in order to measure the hole size and the presence of non-axisymmetric structures. This
requires the use of a very high angular resolution and also controls the required exposure
time.
Note that, although the largest structures (the gaseous disk extends up to 1000 AU; Fang et al.
2015) will not be recoverable, this is not a problem for our science goals since 1) we are
interested in the innermost disk only and 2) the outer disk has been already resolved in 
continuum and 12CO using the SMA (Fang et al. 2015). This is why the largest angular size 
requested is much smaller than the disk size: it corresponds to the innermost disk up to a 
radius of ~100 AU, which includes the three stars and the locations where the gap and the 
strongest gravitational perturbations are expected to occur.</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_ANGULAR_RESOLUTION</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
        <prj:TechnicalJustification>
            <prj:justificationText>The fluxes, velocities and time estimated are based on our (low angular resolution) SMA
observations (Fang et al. 2015), and assuming an inner hole size in agreement with our SED
modeling (which incorporates wavelengths from near-IR to mm; Fang et al. 2014). Using dynamical
models, we have also estimated the size and depth of the gravitational perturbations caused by
the triple system (Fig. 2). 
A high S/N and angular resolution in the continuum is required to detect asymmetries in
the dust distribution (disk rims, rings, and gaps).
The 12CO observations impose the strongest exposure time constraint. We choose the 12CO(2-1) line
to trace the gas since it is the brigthest and allows us to detect details at high angular scales
within a reasonable time. Even though CO can be affected by saturation and depletion, the SMA
data shows that the disk is very bright in CO, and we will be able to detect perturbations in the
gas as expected from the dynamical models (Fig. 2). The line requirements are based on the SMA
data, assuming the disk is undisturbed (Fang et al. 2015).
From our SMA+SED-based models, the expected peak flux is 0.100575 Jy/pixel*km/s, and the line
width (fwhm) in the inner disk (considering that we aim to obtain details of the innermost
disk) is about 1.57 km/s for  the spatial resolution 0.05 arcsec. The velocity resolution is
selected to probe deviations from Keplerian rotation (see below).</prj:justificationText>
            <prj:justificationKey>ED_SENSITIVITY</prj:justificationKey>
        </prj:TechnicalJustification>
