    <prp:abstract>GW Ori is a triple-star system with a large and bright disk. The central G-type star is surrounded by two low-mass companions at 1 and 8 AU. Near-IR data has shown that the dust content in the innermost disk varies in timescales of ~15 yr, suggestive of a leaky dust filter triggered by GW Ori C. Our gas and dust simulations predict that the gravitational perturbations induced by the companions will cause rings and density waves beyond their orbits. Unlike in other disks with holes/gaps, here we know the position and properties of the companions (via radial velocity and nIR interferometry) and the disk (SMA observations): GW Ori is unique to witness the interaction of a massive disk with its multiple companions. We will use ALMA to study the disk asymmetries and their relation with the perturbing companions, massive enough to produce large, detectable effects. Our good knowledge of the companions and disk for GW Ori allow us to use it as a benchmark to understand the role of multiple companions/planets in driving disk asymmetries in and beyond their orbits. Future observations could also explore the time dimension (on human timescales) and stability of the disk perturbations.</prp:abstract>
